---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from 'astrowind:config';
import JsonLd from '~/components/common/JsonLd.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: `SUP Paddling Techniques — ${SITE.name}`,
  description: 'Master forward stroke, sweep turn, reverse stroke, cross-bow turn, and bracing techniques for efficient and confident SUP paddling.',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <JsonLd type="Article" article={{
    headline: 'SUP Paddling Techniques',
    description: 'Master forward stroke, sweep turn, reverse stroke, cross-bow turn, and bracing techniques for efficient and confident SUP paddling.',
    datePublished: '2025-01-01',
  }} data={{ url: 'https://alluredna.com/guides/paddling-techniques' }} />
  <JsonLd type="HowTo" howto={{
    name: 'SUP Paddling Techniques',
    description: 'Master forward stroke, sweep turn, reverse stroke, cross-bow turn, and bracing techniques.',
    steps: [
      { name: 'The Forward Stroke', text: 'The foundation of all SUP paddling. Reach forward with the paddle blade, submerge it fully, and pull it back alongside the board using torso rotation.' },
      { name: 'The Sweep Turn', text: 'For wide, controlled turns. Reach the paddle wide to the side and sweep in a half-circle toward the tail. Practice on both sides.' },
      { name: 'The Reverse Stroke', text: 'Used for slowing down, stopping, and backing up. Plant the paddle blade behind you and push forward close to the board.' },
      { name: 'The Cross-Bow Turn', text: 'An advanced technique for quick direction changes. Reach across the nose of the board and plant the paddle on the opposite side.' },
      { name: 'Bracing', text: 'A low brace slaps the blade flat on the water to prevent falling. A high brace keeps the paddle shaft horizontal above your head.' },
      { name: 'Cadence & Pacing', text: 'For distance paddling find 40-50 strokes per minute. For recreational cruising 30-40 strokes per minute is comfortable.' },
    ],
  }} />
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-24 px-6" data-ai-block="definition">
    <a href="/guides" class="text-sm text-sky-600 hover:text-sky-700">← Guides</a>
    <h1 class="mt-4 text-4xl font-semibold text-gray-900">SUP Paddling Techniques</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-gray-500">Efficient technique makes paddling smoother, faster, and more enjoyable.</p>

    <div class="mt-12 space-y-12">
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">The Forward Stroke</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">The foundation of all SUP paddling. Reach forward with the paddle blade, submerge it fully to the shaft, and pull it back alongside the board. Use torso rotation — not arm strength — for power. Switch sides every 5-10 strokes to maintain straight tracking. On the SUP Tour 12, consistent stroke rhythm maximizes glide between strokes.</p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">The Sweep Turn</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">For wide, controlled turns. Reach the paddle wide to the side and sweep in a half-circle toward the tail. The wider and deeper the sweep, the sharper the turn. Practice on both sides until the motion feels natural. This is the primary turning technique for all-around boards like the SUP Explorer 11.</p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">The Reverse Stroke</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">Used for slowing down, stopping, and backing up. Plant the paddle blade behind you and push forward. Keep the blade close to the board for control. Combine a reverse stroke on one side with a forward stroke on the other for a pivot turn — useful in tight spaces.</p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">The Cross-Bow Turn</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">An advanced technique for quick direction changes without switching paddle sides. Reach across the nose of the board and plant the paddle on the opposite side. This is efficient for downwind paddling and surfing where quick reactions matter.</p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Bracing</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">A low brace uses the paddle as a stabilizer — slap the blade flat on the water surface to prevent falling. A high brace is more powerful and keeps the paddle shaft horizontal above your head. Practice bracing in calm water before relying on it in rough conditions.</p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Cadence & Pacing</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">For distance paddling on the SUP Tour 12, find a sustainable cadence of 40-50 strokes per minute with a 10-stroke sprint every 5 minutes. For recreational cruising on the SUP Explorer 11, 30-40 strokes per minute is comfortable. Listen to your body and adjust.</p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <section class="mt-12 p-6 bg-sky-50 rounded-2xl border border-sky-100">
      <h2 class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3 text-sm">
        <a href="/guides/beginner-guide" class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 text-gray-700 hover:border-sky-300">Beginner Guide</a>
        <a href="/guides/sup-fitness" class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 text-gray-700 hover:border-sky-300">SUP for Fitness</a>
        <a href="/guides/kayak-techniques" class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 text-gray-700 hover:border-sky-300">Kayak Techniques</a>
        <a href="/guides/choosing-paddle" class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 text-gray-700 hover:border-sky-300">Choosing a Paddle</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</Layout>
